1772916421302360	bob	itc:v3:AWKSc8kyZJPJk5EAAAAAQau9WtV610AAAAEz4gI		item.create	bn-1zzt	{"description":"Project: Make edict support pluggable org tooling and instruction packs without losing its core semantics.\n\nPrimary objective:\nDesign and implement a pluggable architecture where edict remains the canonical workflow/control plane, while native tools (rite, bones, crit, seal) and external org tools (Slack, Jira, GitHub) are implemented as adapters and policy packs.\n\nHard constraints:\n1. Edict is the canonical source of workflow state.\n2. Claims/leases remain internal to edict.\n3. External tools are projections/adapters, not the source of truth.\n4. v1 target stack is Slack + Jira + GitHub.\n5. v1 is not a generic workflow engine and does not require full bidirectional sync.\n6. No provider-specific statuses, IDs, or semantics may leak into the core domain model.\n\nWhat I need from you:\nBreak this project down into goals, subgoals, and implementation tasks with dependencies, acceptance criteria, and recommended sequencing.\n\nRequired phases:\n\nPhase 0 — Thesis and MVP boundary\n- Produce an ADR locking source of truth, non-goals, and MVP provider set.\n- Define the single reference workflow for v1.\n- Define success metrics.\n\nPhase 1 — Native semantic inventory\n- Inventory concepts and invariants across edict, rite, bones, crit, seal.\n- Classify each concept as canonical/internal, adapter-provided, or optional.\n- Identify hidden assumptions in prompts/instructions.\n\nPhase 2 — Canonical domain model\n- Define schemas for WorkItem, Claim/Lease, Conversation, Review, Artifact/EvidenceBundle, PolicyPack, Principal, Run, Event, ExternalRef.\n- Define lifecycle/state machine and provenance model.\n- Define stable IDs and mapping rules.\n\nPhase 3 — Adapter contracts and capability model\n- Define adapter families: Comms, Tasks, Review, Evidence, Identity.\n- Define capability discovery and degradation rules.\n- Define idempotency, retry, error, and rate-limit semantics.\n- Produce conformance tests and fake adapters.\n\nPhase 4 — Policy/instruction pack system\n- Separate protocol from org policy from rendering.\n- Define pack schema, overlays, validation, and conflict resolution.\n- Implement example packs for native stack and Slack/Jira/GitHub.\n\nPhase 5 — Projection and reconciliation\n- Implement outbound projection to Slack/Jira/GitHub.\n- Implement narrow inbound event ingestion.\n- Define reconciliation and audit rules.\n\nPhase 6 — End-to-end MVP\n- Implement the reference workflow end to end.\n- Add integration tests, failure injection, runbooks, and onboarding docs.\n\nPhase 7 — Abstraction validation\n- Add a second pack or provider to prove the contracts are real and not overfit.\n\nInstructions for decomposition:\n- Break goals into tasks sized roughly 0.5–2 days where possible.\n- Distinguish research spikes from implementation tasks.\n- Include dependencies for every task.\n- Include acceptance criteria for every goal and major task.\n- Call out all risky/uncertain areas explicitly.\n- Do not schedule adapter implementation work before the semantic inventory, domain model, and adapter contract work are complete.\n- Prefer one strong reference workflow over broad incomplete coverage.\n\nDeliverables format:\n- Goal tree\n- Dependency graph\n- Ordered task list\n- Risks/open questions\n- Suggested milestone plan","kind":"task","labels":["plan"],"title":"plan to support pluggable tooling"}	blake3:XoIvF4FLKEXwD6VLWgdPQ8stgdAO5dzblQll-Ux7qic
1772917139056850	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvBw		item.create	bn-3g8f	{"description":"Define the foundational decisions for pluggable tooling v1.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- ADR published covering source-of-truth stance, non-goals, MVP provider set\n- Single reference workflow selected and documented\n- Success metrics defined\n\nAll tasks in this phase require user decisions. See child tasks.","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P0: thesis and MVP boundary"}	blake3:a-MkpwEUZxKI6uXTR3XsKAjCtFBFT9h2CxH7iL7ORNY
1772917142167682	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvCA		item.create	bn-3gr0	{"description":"Inventory and classify all concepts and invariants across the current tool suite.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Complete concept inventory across edict, rite, bones, seal, maw\n- Each concept classified as canonical/internal, adapter-provided, or optional\n- All hardcoded tool assumptions in prompts/templates identified\n- Decision: clarify whether \"crit\" (referenced in parent bone) is planned or stale","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P1: native semantic inventory"}	blake3:MxHM4E-quC3Sjy_zmhD5Hn0TaME1hQFnhOtIYVckEGY
1772917145318004	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvCQ		item.create	bn-3lpn	{"description":"Define the core domain model that adapters will target.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Entity schemas defined for MVP-relevant types (WorkItem, Claim/Lease, Conversation, Review, ExternalRef at minimum)\n- Lifecycle state machines documented with valid transitions\n- Stable ID scheme defined with mapping rules for external IDs\n- Provenance model tracks which adapter produced each entity/event\n\nNote: defer PolicyPack, EvidenceBundle, and other non-MVP entities to Phase 7 validation.","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P2: canonical domain model"}	blake3:COgDymUNpXe3KQvvEDzTR1qPYswYvS6WBMmyXHIUZlo
1772917148486343	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvCg		item.create	bn-31s3	{"description":"Define the trait/interface contracts that adapters must implement.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Adapter families defined: Comms, Tasks, Review, Identity (defer Evidence to post-MVP)\n- Capability discovery: adapters declare what they support, core degrades gracefully\n- Error, retry, idempotency, and rate-limit semantics documented\n- Conformance test suite runnable against any adapter implementation\n- At least one fake/in-memory adapter passes conformance tests","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P3: adapter contracts and capability model"}	blake3:zjvH1zeo4G4PEd4JBQC63Tl48oiH1QJqVPrKhA3s2rs
1772917151339638	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvCw		item.create	bn-1m4f	{"description":"Build the system that separates protocol logic from org-specific policy and tool-specific rendering.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Clean separation between protocol (edict core), policy (org rules), and rendering (tool-specific templates)\n- Pack schema defined with overlay/composition rules\n- Pack validation catches conflicts and missing capabilities\n- Native stack reference pack implemented and passing\n- AGENTS.md, workflow docs, and hook commands are generated from pack, not hardcoded","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P4: policy and instruction pack system"}	blake3:5RJy5VHIk9ZjYL_eEodzbw8aMWANb14cFqN5n7DpVWg
1772917155006078	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvDA		item.create	bn-1ex1	{"description":"Implement outbound projection to external providers and narrow inbound ingestion.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Outbound projection working for Slack, Jira, and GitHub\n- Narrow inbound event ingestion defined and implemented (scope locked in P0 ADR)\n- Reconciliation rules catch drift between edict state and external state\n- Audit log tracks all projections and ingestions\n\nMultiple tasks in this phase require credentials and provider setup. See child tasks.","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P5: projection and reconciliation"}	blake3:H7kqmGq8e5qNbojWRqNzSMfmWV84k-a-2sAGuBFERXs
1772917156727047	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvDQ		item.create	bn-30fe	{"description":"Wire the reference workflow end-to-end and validate with real providers.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Reference workflow (defined in P0) runs end-to-end through adapters\n- Integration tests cover happy path and key failure modes\n- Failure injection tests verify degradation behavior\n- Runbook and onboarding docs written","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P6: end-to-end MVP"}	blake3:kzjoqYZFrAMhqPkRzcFyid4dwAz6yBgtPKxfQMopoMY
1772917160774029	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvDg		item.create	bn-1bny	{"description":"Prove the adapter contracts are real abstractions, not overfit to the v1 provider set.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Second provider pack (or significantly different adapter) implemented\n- No contract changes needed to support the second provider (or contracts fixed if needed)\n- Documented what was overfit and what generalized cleanly\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED: Choose which second provider or pack to implement (e.g., Discord, Linear, GitLab, or a completely different category).","kind":"goal","title":"pluggable-tooling P7: abstraction validation"}	blake3:GE0QixKvOAIfwixHTSWyatto4ORXwmgkxpuHtUFJ5xA
1772917182143600	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvDw		item.create	bn-331i	{"description":"Write the ADR that locks all foundational decisions for pluggable tooling.\n\nDeliverables:\n- ADR in notes/proposals/ covering source-of-truth stance, non-goals, MVP provider set, reference workflow, success metrics\n\nUSER DECISIONS REQUIRED (punt until decided):\n1. Confirm source-of-truth stance: edict is canonical, external tools are projections/adapters (not sources of truth)\n2. Confirm non-goals: not a generic workflow engine, no full bidirectional sync in v1\n3. Confirm v1 provider set (proposed: Slack + Jira + GitHub)\n4. Select reference workflow for v1 (proposed: single-bone worker cycle — triage → claim → workspace → implement → review → merge → close)\n5. Define success metrics (what does \"working\" look like?)\n6. Clarify: \"crit\" is referenced in bn-1zzt but absent from the current ecosystem table — is it planned, renamed, or stale?\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- ADR published and approved\n- All 6 decisions above resolved","kind":"task","labels":["needs-user"],"title":"P0: write foundational ADR"}	blake3:sqV4nYEp1bgmLFEwrYrC2uq_7zBz-Fx-vWbV2sOlZNs
1772917189377037	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvEA		item.create	bn-1lwb	{"description":"Research spike. Enumerate every domain concept and invariant across the five tools.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Spreadsheet/table of concepts: name, owning tool, description, invariants, current storage, API surface\n- Cover at minimum: WorkItem/Bone, Channel/Message, Claim/Lease, Review/Thread/Vote, Workspace/Worktree, Agent/Principal, Hook/Trigger, Label, State machine transitions\n\nMethod:\n- Read source code for each tool's data model\n- Read CLI help and man pages\n- Read AGENTS.md managed section for implicit concepts\n- Grep templates/ and prompts/ for hardcoded tool names and command patterns\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- No concept used in edict prompts or templates is missing from the inventory\n- Each concept has its invariants documented (e.g., \"a bone can only transition open→doing→done, never backwards\")","kind":"task","title":"P1: inventory concepts across edict, rite, bones, seal, maw"}	blake3:Jbi4BCnJ_NL0q-rU6YyAwUbDoir8KDyxooOHH66_p6s
1772917197093295	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvEQ		item.create	bn-1pfq	{"description":"Using the inventory from the previous task, classify each concept and find all hardcoded assumptions.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Classification table — each concept tagged as:\n   - canonical/internal (must exist in edict core, e.g., Claim, WorkItem state machine)\n   - adapter-provided (comes from external tool, e.g., message threading, PR comments)\n   - optional (nice-to-have, degrade gracefully if absent, e.g., rich formatting)\n\n2. Template/prompt audit — list of every place in src/templates/, .agents/edict/, and prompts/ that:\n   - References a specific tool by name (rite, bn, seal, maw, vessel)\n   - Hardcodes a command syntax (e.g., \"bn create --title\")\n   - Assumes a specific output format\n   - Assumes a specific data model (e.g., \"bone has state open/doing/done\")\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Every concept classified\n- Every hardcoded tool reference catalogued with file:line\n- Assessment of which assumptions are fundamental vs adapter-specific","kind":"task","title":"P1: classify concepts and audit template assumptions"}	blake3:kLqgNY9rpVGL2HGMfuDB6Pc0TcTbzbexiz4pfQ_ZfOo
1772917202609303	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvEg		item.create	bn-2y0r	{"description":"Define the Rust types for the canonical domain model.\n\nEntities for MVP:\n- WorkItem (generalizes Bone): id, title, description, state, kind, labels, assignees, comments, timestamps\n- Claim/Lease: uri, agent, memo, ttl, timestamps\n- Conversation: channel, messages, participants, labels, threading\n- Review: id, workspace, title, reviewers, threads, votes, state\n- ExternalRef: maps edict internal IDs ↔ external provider IDs (bidirectional lookup)\n\nDefer to post-MVP: PolicyPack, EvidenceBundle, Artifact, Run\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Rust types defined with serde support\n- Types are provider-agnostic (no Slack/Jira/GitHub-specific fields)\n- ExternalRef supports multiple external IDs per internal entity\n- Types have doc comments explaining invariants","kind":"task","title":"P2: define core entity schemas"}	blake3:n75W5EX-FEx5WTqnOQrXae9RfGqkIBYw4XkHw_AVs8U
1772917207537530	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvEw		item.create	bn-1q3j	{"description":"Define valid state transitions for each entity and track provenance.\n\nDeliverables:\n- State machine for WorkItem (generalizes bone states, must support external provider states mapping)\n- State machine for Review (create → pending → approved/blocked → merged)\n- State machine for Claim (staked → refreshed → released/expired)\n- Provenance model: each entity/event records which adapter produced it and when\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- State machines are exhaustive (every valid transition documented)\n- Invalid transitions produce clear errors\n- External provider states map cleanly onto canonical states (document any lossy mappings)\n- Provenance is queryable: \"who created this and via which adapter?\"","kind":"task","title":"P2: define lifecycle state machines and provenance"}	blake3:LD8yzSKxo8RGmnnKVn-2YopG2xLjtjRDPY0oNFwpKVA
1772917212921946	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvFA		item.create	bn-20z1	{"description":"Define the ID scheme that bridges edict internal IDs with external provider IDs.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Internal ID format (current bones use short hashes like bn-XXXX — preserve or evolve?)\n- ExternalRef mapping table design: internal_id ↔ (provider, external_id) with lookup in both directions\n- Rules for ID stability: what happens when an entity exists in multiple providers?\n- Rules for orphaned refs: external entity deleted but edict ref remains\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Bidirectional lookup: internal→external and external→internal\n- No provider-specific IDs leak into core model\n- Handles the case where same logical entity has refs in multiple providers\n- Migration path from current bone IDs to new scheme (if changed)","kind":"task","title":"P2: define stable IDs and mapping rules"}	blake3:X0rsfct-ERGcohOfxg1cNn-6X56Dn1-GJ646g0VYcnA
1772917219806124	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvFQ		item.create	bn-35dj	{"description":"Define the Rust trait interfaces for each adapter family.\n\nFamilies:\n1. Comms — send/receive messages, channels, threading, mentions (generalizes rite)\n2. Tasks — CRUD work items, state transitions, queries, search (generalizes bones)\n3. Review — create reviews, comment, vote, thread (generalizes seal)\n4. Identity — resolve agent/user principals, permissions (generalizes rite whoami + claims)\n\nDefer: Evidence (artifact/bundle storage) — not needed for MVP\n\nDesign constraints:\n- Traits are async\n- Methods return domain model types, not provider types\n- Each trait method documents whether it's required or optional (capability-based)\n- Traits include batch/list operations where relevant\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Trait definitions compile\n- Each method has doc comments with semantics and error conditions\n- Native adapters (wrapping rite/bones/seal) can implement these traits\n- No provider-specific types in trait signatures","kind":"task","title":"P3: define adapter family interfaces"}	blake3:2zYtIwfkKPinv0iYfYIKzNahaCX7Whj4JT5i2VWUEr4
1772917225297599	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvFg		item.create	bn-y8xf	{"description":"Define how edict discovers what an adapter can do and handles missing capabilities.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Capability model:\n   - Each adapter declares capabilities (e.g., Comms supports threading? mentions? reactions?)\n   - Core queries capabilities before using optional features\n   - Graceful degradation when capability is absent (e.g., no threading → flat messages)\n\n2. Error semantics:\n   - Idempotency: which operations are safe to retry? How to detect duplicates?\n   - Retry policy: exponential backoff, max retries, circuit breaker\n   - Rate limiting: adapter reports limits, core respects them\n   - Transient vs permanent errors: adapter classifies, core acts accordingly\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Capability enum/bitflag defined for each adapter family\n- Degradation behavior documented for every optional capability\n- Error types defined with retry guidance\n- Rate limit protocol defined","kind":"task","title":"P3: define capability discovery, degradation, and error semantics"}	blake3:wHNGp0lI4rKhbsHR4FzzNwafVWpeEU2zhFriusKzbdU
1772917236702511	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvFw		item.create	bn-1d8o	{"description":"Build the test infrastructure that validates adapter implementations.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Conformance test suite: exercises every required trait method, checks invariants, validates error handling\n2. Fake/in-memory adapters: implement all four adapter families using in-memory storage (no external deps)\n3. Native adapters: wrap rite, bones, seal as adapters implementing the new traits\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Fake adapters pass full conformance suite\n- Native adapters pass full conformance suite\n- Tests are reusable: any new adapter can run the same suite\n- Tests cover: CRUD, state transitions, concurrent access, error conditions","kind":"task","title":"P3: build conformance test suite and fake adapters"}	blake3:wC57nmKuwA_PYYdk3nQAAzMVh1XE3c1X7nRLYXLL9zo
1772917244926814	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvGA		item.create	bn-1ftr	{"description":"Refactor edict's current monolithic templates into three clean layers.\n\nLayers:\n1. Protocol — the workflow state machine and adapter orchestration (edict core, not configurable)\n2. Policy — org-specific rules: review requirements, naming conventions, commit message format, which reviewers to assign (configurable per org)\n3. Rendering — tool-specific templates: how to generate AGENTS.md, hook commands, CLI examples for a given adapter set (determined by active adapters)\n\nDeliverables:\n- Pack schema (TOML or similar) defining: metadata, required capabilities, policy overrides, template overrides\n- Overlay/composition rules: base pack + org overlay → final config\n- Validation: catch conflicts (e.g., policy requires threading but Comms adapter doesn't support it)\n- Conflict resolution rules documented\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Schema is defined and documented\n- Validation catches at least 3 categories of pack errors\n- A pack can be loaded, validated, and composed with an overlay","kind":"task","title":"P4: separate protocol/policy/rendering and define pack schema"}	blake3:-ZDx4c3BkQppy_zq28kSHjCmpni4Hr5hhIILp6oUTsI
1772917250754705	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvGQ		item.create	bn-27tk	{"description":"Implement a pack that reproduces edict's current behavior using the new pack system.\n\nThis is the critical validation step: the new system must produce identical (or functionally equivalent) output to the current hardcoded templates.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Native pack defining: rite as Comms, bones as Tasks, seal as Review, rite+claims as Identity\n- Templates rewritten to use pack abstractions instead of hardcoded tool names\n- AGENTS.md generation via pack (replaces current agents-managed.md template)\n- Hook registration via pack (replaces current hardcoded hook commands)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- edict sync with native pack produces functionally equivalent output to current edict sync\n- All existing evals still pass\n- No regression in agent behavior","kind":"task","title":"P4: build native stack reference pack"}	blake3:6pWsh3XETY-EboWDUOjvqqMFK8LsOIn9pmYe-BqQR9Y
1772917256866991	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvGg		item.create	bn-2opv	{"description":"Create the pack definition for the v1 external provider set. Skeleton only — actual adapter implementation is in P5.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Pack file mapping: Slack as Comms, Jira as Tasks, GitHub as Review, GitHub/Slack as Identity\n- Templates generating Slack/Jira/GitHub-specific AGENTS.md sections and hook commands\n- Capability declarations (e.g., Slack supports threading and mentions, Jira supports custom fields)\n- Documentation of capability gaps vs native stack (what degrades)\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED:\n- Confirm provider-to-family mapping (Slack=Comms, Jira=Tasks, GitHub=Review)\n- Any org-specific policy overrides to include in the pack\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Pack loads and validates without errors\n- edict sync with this pack produces a coherent AGENTS.md (even if adapters aren't wired yet)\n- Capability gaps documented","kind":"task","labels":["needs-user"],"title":"P4: build Slack/Jira/GitHub pack skeleton"}	blake3:nUAL_SKjHknrG68qU5DNiOazn0InyocTDwLhqJg6Kfc
1772917269625355	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvGw		item.create	bn-2fgd	{"description":"Set up API access for Slack, Jira, and GitHub for adapter development and testing.\n\nUSER ACTION REQUIRED — this task is entirely on you:\n\nSlack:\n- Create Slack app or bot token with channels:read, channels:history, chat:write, reactions:read scopes\n- Provide bot token and signing secret\n- Designate test channel(s)\n\nJira:\n- Create API token (or OAuth app) with project read/write access\n- Provide base URL, project key, and credentials\n- Designate test project\n\nGitHub:\n- Create GitHub App or PAT with repo, issues, pull_requests scopes\n- Provide token and target repo(s)\n- Designate test repository\n\nDeliverable: credentials stored securely (env vars, secrets file, or vault) and documented in a non-committed .env.example\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Each provider's API is reachable with provided credentials\n- Test resources (channel, project, repo) exist and are writable","kind":"task","labels":["needs-user","needs-credentials"],"title":"P5: set up external provider credentials and access"}	blake3:cANgQ5h7g0wYRD5OpIN-QyNMgXBFHBJZnDXOc0biNF4
1772917270203903	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHA		item.create	bn-2ou4	{"description":"Implement the adapter code that projects edict state to external providers.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Slack Comms adapter: send messages to channels, support threading if available, handle mentions\n- Jira Tasks adapter: create/update issues, map WorkItem states to Jira statuses, sync comments\n- GitHub Review adapter: create PR comments, map review threads, handle LGTM/BLOCK as GitHub review states\n\nDesign constraints:\n- Projections are eventually consistent, not synchronous\n- Each projection is idempotent (safe to replay)\n- Use ExternalRef to track what's been projected and avoid duplicates\n- Respect rate limits from capability model\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Each adapter passes the conformance test suite from P3\n- Projections are idempotent (running twice produces same external state)\n- Rate limiting works (adapter backs off when throttled)\n- ExternalRef mappings are created for every projected entity","kind":"task","title":"P5: implement outbound projections to Slack/Jira/GitHub"}	blake3:TGmt3BkJmEpDGYRc58VSDNbotnJUk-PBb-CzUdAh5fk
1772917277898891	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHQ		item.create	bn-bh89	{"description":"Implement narrow inbound event handling and drift detection.\n\nInbound scope (define precisely in P0 ADR, but likely):\n- Slack: message reactions or thread replies that constitute approvals/feedback\n- Jira: status changes made by humans in Jira UI\n- GitHub: PR review submissions, comment replies\n\nNOT in scope for v1 (per hard constraint #5):\n- Full bidirectional sync\n- External entity creation flowing back as new edict WorkItems\n- Real-time webhooks (polling is acceptable for v1)\n\nReconciliation:\n- Periodic drift check: compare edict state vs external state\n- Log discrepancies to audit trail\n- Define resolution rules (edict wins? external wins? alert?)\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED:\n- Confirm which inbound events to support in v1\n- Confirm conflict resolution policy (proposed: edict wins, log discrepancy)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Inbound events update edict state correctly\n- Drift detection catches at least: state mismatch, missing external entity, orphaned ref\n- Audit log records all reconciliation actions","kind":"task","labels":["needs-user"],"title":"P5: implement inbound event ingestion and reconciliation"}	blake3:OvORg9BqR186aaohW7UkUCTxtdZmpnPHSmDdARZnwq4
1772917283729298	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHg		item.create	bn-1rut	{"description":"Run the reference workflow (defined in P0) from start to finish using external adapters.\n\nSteps (assuming worker cycle reference workflow):\n1. Work request arrives (via Slack message or Jira issue creation)\n2. Edict creates WorkItem, projects to Jira\n3. Agent claims work, creates workspace\n4. Agent implements, commits\n5. Review created, projected to GitHub PR\n6. Reviewer reviews via GitHub or seal\n7. Review approved, workspace merged\n8. WorkItem closed, Jira issue transitioned, Slack notification sent\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Full cycle completes without manual intervention\n- All external projections visible in Slack/Jira/GitHub\n- ExternalRef mappings correct at every step\n- Degradation works: disable one adapter, workflow still completes with reduced functionality","kind":"task","title":"P6: wire reference workflow end to end"}	blake3:A_nZtnFb0WfAHFkVxh7D4L-88qwVy2eBxyCaG7UahRw
1772917302448000	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvHw		item.create	bn-3a8i	{"description":"Build the test and documentation infrastructure for the MVP.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Integration tests:\n   - Happy path: full reference workflow with fake adapters\n   - Adapter failure: each adapter fails mid-workflow, verify degradation\n   - Rate limiting: adapter throttles, verify backoff works\n   - Concurrent access: multiple agents working through adapters simultaneously\n\n2. Failure injection:\n   - Network failures between edict and external providers\n   - Partial failures (projection succeeds to Slack, fails to Jira)\n   - Stale ExternalRef (external entity deleted)\n\n3. Documentation:\n   - Runbook: troubleshooting adapter failures, reconciliation drift, credential rotation\n   - Onboarding guide: how to set up edict with external providers\n   - Pack authoring guide: how to create a new pack\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Integration tests run in CI with fake adapters (no real credentials needed)\n- At least 5 failure injection scenarios tested\n- Runbook covers top 10 expected failure modes\n- Onboarding guide tested by someone who hasn't used the system","kind":"task","title":"P6: integration tests, failure injection, and docs"}	blake3:SOtOubUWj-Fj0b0X-WH26MLv60Ec1EAdFp2VoGls1VY
1772917308827071	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvIA		item.create	bn-1njj	{"description":"Implement a second provider to validate the adapter contracts aren't overfit.\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED:\n- Choose second provider set. Options:\n  a) Discord (Comms) + Linear (Tasks) + GitLab (Review) — similar category, different APIs\n  b) Matrix (Comms) + Notion (Tasks) + Gerrit (Review) — very different paradigms\n  c) Mix: one provider from a different category (e.g., replace just Comms with Discord)\n  d) Something else entirely\n\nThe choice should maximize contract stress-testing. Option (b) is the most rigorous but also the most work.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Second pack loads, validates, and passes edict sync\n- Second provider adapters pass the conformance test suite from P3\n- Document which contract assumptions broke and had to be fixed","kind":"task","labels":["needs-user"],"title":"P7: choose and implement second provider pack"}	blake3:VnIo9aimq97cA6UBKh093jsX3oIh-zcBfoMwPLuWeHY
1772917313217359	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvIQ		item.create	bn-1qv0	{"description":"After implementing the second provider, assess and fix any overfit in the contracts.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Audit report: which trait methods, capability flags, or schema fields were overfit to v1 providers\n- Contract fixes: generalize any overfit abstractions\n- Regression check: ensure v1 provider pack still passes after fixes\n- Final assessment: are the contracts genuinely provider-agnostic or do they need another round?\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Both provider packs pass conformance suite after any contract changes\n- No provider-specific types or assumptions remain in core domain model\n- Documented lessons learned for future adapter authors","kind":"task","title":"P7: validate contracts and fix overfit"}	blake3:vZKEHKQp4PpyNSfobICE2DUowk5Y0Y1sq8maZLLF6t4
