1772917922925529	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvdg		item.update	bn-1njj	{"field":"urgency","value":"punt"}	blake3:5oSPWgeUbSuvdC8ULm7C05PNyWArZbijQKNC6tor31E
1772925446325952	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvdw		item.comment	bn-331i	{"body":"Decision: Source of truth is Option C (split ownership) with a migration path toward Option A.\n\n- Edict-canonical: claims, leases, agent identity, workspace state — things external tools don't model\n- External-canonical: ticket lifecycle (Jira), PR review state (GitHub), message threading (Slack) — where humans already work\n- Adapters must declare which entity fields they own vs mirror\n- Goal: orgs start at C (pragmatic adoption) and can progressively move ownership into edict as trust builds\n\nThe ADR should document the ownership split per entity type and the migration path from C→A."}	blake3:tuHjQcnZGnvnsYC7C6uyL8ig7ZptnZhhgLi8aMG-Hio
1772925729569513	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEveA		item.comment	bn-331i	{"body":"Decision: Non-goals confirmed.\n\n1. Not a generic workflow engine — adapters make tools pluggable, not the process\n2. No full bidirectional sync in v1 — narrow inbound ingestion only, no closed-loop sync\n3. Not multi-tenant — one edict instance = one project\n4. Not a replacement for external tools — edict coordinates through them, doesn't obsolete them\n5. Offline mode is not a non-goal per se — the native stack (rite, seal, bones) already works offline. External adapters naturally require network, but that's inherent, not a design constraint.\n\nNote: UI is a non-goal for now but leave the door open for future private SaaS. Don't make architectural decisions that would prevent it."}	blake3:jd5mAmwjE3RA0tMUoT7sH9C5Da-zaVMp2TjjJlzZdf0
1772926164468664	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEveQ		item.comment	bn-331i	{"body":"Decision: V1 scope is task tracker pluggability only.\n\nV1 provider set: Jira + GitHub Issues (both as Tasks adapters)\n\nWhat stays native (not pluggable in v1):\n- rite — claims, hooks, coordination, messaging. No replacement.\n- seal — code review. No replacement.\n- maw — workspaces. No replacement.\n\nWhat's pluggable:\n- bones → Jira or GitHub Issues (task/work-item tracking)\n\nCut from v1:\n- Slack (not even as notifications — cut entirely)\n- Comms adapter family — rite stays, no adapter needed\n- Review adapter family — seal stays, no adapter needed  \n- Identity adapter family — not needed when only Tasks is pluggable\n\nThis significantly reduces scope across P1-P7. Bones need restructuring."}	blake3:Ibs1iBSohT7C9LP-LL-rcQLiVtM7Ll_PsC0OMrWenTw
1772926221072370	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEveg		item.update	bn-331i	{"field":"description","value":"Write the ADR that locks all foundational decisions for pluggable tooling.\n\nDeliverables:\n- ADR in notes/proposals/ covering source-of-truth stance, non-goals, MVP provider set, reference workflow, success metrics\n\nUSER DECISIONS REQUIRED (punt until decided):\n1. DECIDED — Source of truth: split ownership (Option C) with migration path to A. Edict owns claims/leases/agent identity/workspace state. External tools own their native state (Jira ticket lifecycle, GitHub issue state). Adapters declare ownership per field.\n2. DECIDED — Non-goals: not a generic workflow engine, no full bidirectional sync in v1, not multi-tenant, not a replacement for external tools. UI is non-goal for now but don't preclude future SaaS. Offline isn't a constraint — native stack works offline, external adapters inherently need network.\n3. DECIDED — V1 scope: task tracker pluggability only. Bones → Jira or GitHub Issues. Rite/seal/maw stay native. Slack cut from v1.\n4. Select reference workflow for v1 (proposed: single-bone worker cycle — triage → claim → workspace → implement → review → merge → close)\n5. Define success metrics (what does \"working\" look like?)\n6. Clarify: \"crit\" is referenced in bn-1zzt but absent from the current ecosystem table — is it planned, renamed, or stale?\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- ADR published and approved\n- All 6 decisions above resolved"}	blake3:AU6xsxVw5a7a4rHHeSm2i2nWvKp_23DFiRUJq6DHOXM
1772926226762076	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvew		item.update	bn-3g8f	{"field":"description","value":"Define the foundational decisions for pluggable tooling v1.\n\nV1 scope: task tracker pluggability only (bones → Jira or GitHub Issues). Rite, seal, maw stay native. Slack cut.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- ADR published covering source-of-truth stance, non-goals, MVP provider set\n- Single reference workflow selected and documented\n- Success metrics defined\n\nAll tasks in this phase require user decisions. See child tasks."}	blake3:q57wUH94kMvQawmsQYA4s5DYb58sYKiN6uufiEYx5pA
1772926231734859	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvfA		item.update	bn-3gr0	{"field":"description","value":"Inventory and classify all concepts and invariants relevant to task tracker pluggability.\n\nFocus: bones concepts and their equivalents in Jira and GitHub Issues. Rite/seal/maw are staying native — inventory them only to identify coupling points with bones.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Complete concept inventory of bones (WorkItem states, kinds, labels, dependencies, comments, search, triage)\n- Mapping table: bones concept → Jira equivalent → GitHub Issues equivalent\n- All places in edict that hardcode bones commands, output formats, or data model identified\n- Coupling points between bones and rite/seal/maw documented (e.g., bone IDs in claim URIs, bone IDs in review metadata)"}	blake3:UHuzmddt6x3TigZwC_e3Zags85PaNI7fZYcAp6VgdZo
1772926238253276	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvfQ		item.update	bn-1lwb	{"field":"description","value":"Inventory every bones concept used in edict and map to Jira/GitHub Issues equivalents.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Table of bones concepts: bone, state (open/doing/done), kind (task/bug/goal), labels, urgency, dependencies, comments, parent-child, triage scores, search\n- For each concept: where it's used in edict (templates, prompts, agent loops, CLI commands)\n- Mapping to Jira: issue, status, issue type, labels, priority, links, comments, epic/subtask, JQL\n- Mapping to GitHub Issues: issue, state (open/closed), labels, milestones, sub-issues, comments, search\n- Gap analysis: what bones has that Jira/GitHub Issues don't (e.g., triage scores, urgency=punt, dependency graph)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- No bones concept used in edict is missing from the inventory\n- Every concept has Jira and GitHub Issues equivalents documented (or marked as \"no equivalent\")"}	blake3:mf9jt1eFRpAgX-sBwg7cSC8yNHMA2HfDz5gmEk-EcNM
1772926246223475	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvfg		item.update	bn-1pfq	{"field":"description","value":"Classify bones concepts by pluggability and audit edict for hardcoded bones assumptions.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Classification of each bones concept:\n   - Must abstract (used by edict core, adapters must implement): create, state transitions, list/query, comments\n   - Nice to have (degrade gracefully if absent): dependencies, triage scores, parent-child hierarchy, urgency levels\n   - Bones-only (no adapter equivalent, keep as bones-specific): bn-specific ID format, event sourcing internals\n\n2. Audit of edict source code — every place that:\n   - Calls bn/bones CLI commands (grep for \"bn \", \"bn create\", \"bn do\", \"bn done\", etc.)\n   - Parses bones output format\n   - References bones data model (state names, kind names, ID format)\n   - Embeds bones commands in templates or prompts\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Every concept classified\n- Every hardcoded bones reference catalogued with file:line\n- Clear picture of what the Tasks adapter trait needs to support vs what can degrade"}	blake3:IQMQUw2s-ZCoB_BZ3Mhhp34SmWBBX073KbZK4UeUCN8
1772926269586325	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvfw		item.update	bn-3lpn	{"field":"description","value":"Define the core domain model for task tracker abstraction.\n\nScope: WorkItem (generalizes Bone/Jira Issue/GitHub Issue) and ExternalRef (ID mapping). Other entity types (Conversation, Review) are not needed — rite and seal stay native.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- WorkItem schema defined that covers bones, Jira, and GitHub Issues use cases\n- ExternalRef mapping defined for bidirectional ID lookup\n- Lifecycle state machine defined with mapping rules for each provider's states\n- Ownership model per field documented (edict-owned vs external-owned per the split-ownership decision)"}	blake3:6UbfTBI5VkbpNNK_ob_iq58kviut9nhAvgBWaVE2CDU
1772926271134153	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvgAE		item.update	bn-2y0r	{"field":"description","value":"Define the Rust types for WorkItem and ExternalRef.\n\nWorkItem (generalizes Bone):\n- id, title, description, state, kind, labels, assignees, comments, timestamps\n- Optional: dependencies, parent-child, urgency, triage metadata\n- Must be provider-agnostic — no Jira/GitHub-specific fields\n\nExternalRef:\n- internal_id ↔ (provider, external_id) bidirectional mapping\n- Supports multiple external refs per internal entity (same bone tracked in both Jira and GitHub)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Rust types defined with serde support\n- Types cover the union of bones, Jira, and GitHub Issues fields (from P1 inventory)\n- Fields that only some providers support are Optional\n- ExternalRef supports bidirectional lookup\n- Doc comments explain which fields are provider-agnostic vs optional"}	blake3:Q4ppPL6a_QbKo2X7LJfhEj7ge-pTLXfuMUYTl9NlhYg
1772926271761379	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvgQE		item.update	bn-1q3j	{"field":"description","value":"Define valid state transitions for WorkItem and field ownership rules.\n\nDeliverables:\n- WorkItem state machine that generalizes:\n  - bones: open → doing → done\n  - Jira: configurable workflow (To Do → In Progress → In Review → Done, etc.)\n  - GitHub Issues: open → closed (with labels as pseudo-states)\n- Mapping rules: how each provider's states map onto the canonical states (document lossy mappings)\n- Ownership model per field:\n  - edict-owned: fields edict controls, projected outward (e.g., assignee set by agent claim)\n  - external-owned: fields the external tool controls, ingested inward (e.g., Jira priority set by human)\n  - derived: fields computed from other state (e.g., triage score)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- State machine handles all three providers' lifecycle models\n- Lossy mappings documented (e.g., Jira's 8 statuses → edict's 3 states)\n- Ownership declared per field with conflict resolution rules\n- Invalid transitions produce clear errors"}	blake3:QzqLZcCX4kdtvQBPqNAzyVXLhDNcEi0A_FYQwRVDT7U
1772926272082791	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvggE		item.update	bn-20z1	{"field":"description","value":"Define the ID scheme bridging edict internal IDs with Jira/GitHub issue IDs.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Internal ID format (current bones use bn-XXXX — preserve or evolve?)\n- ExternalRef storage: internal_id ↔ (provider, external_id)\n  - Jira: project key + issue number (e.g., PROJ-123)\n  - GitHub: owner/repo + issue number (e.g., org/repo#42)\n- Bidirectional lookup in both directions\n- Rules for: orphaned refs (external deleted), duplicate refs (same entity in multiple providers)\n- Migration path from current bone IDs if format changes\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Bidirectional lookup works: internal→external and external→internal\n- No provider-specific IDs in core model\n- Handles one internal entity mapped to multiple external providers\n- Migration path documented if bone ID format changes"}	blake3:Ax6uon9KoNaIQlyAenSNb8EjipwBlpKxFRTFlc4XVrI
1772926280460300	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvgwE		item.update	bn-31s3	{"field":"description","value":"Define the Tasks adapter trait and build conformance infrastructure.\n\nOne adapter family: Tasks (replaces bones). Two v1 implementations: Jira, GitHub Issues. Plus native bones adapter and in-memory fake.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Tasks trait defined covering WorkItem CRUD, state transitions, queries, comments\n- Capability discovery for optional features (dependencies, parent-child, triage)\n- Error/retry/rate-limit semantics documented\n- Conformance test suite passing against fake and native bones adapters"}	blake3:-sHqmt9cr57SjyghCRIDru0sa0FSYxKtNAmlWbVj-Zg
1772926289028563	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvhAE		item.update	bn-35dj	{"field":"description","value":"Define the Rust trait for the Tasks adapter family.\n\nThe Tasks trait generalizes bones operations used by edict:\n- create(WorkItem) → id\n- get(id) → WorkItem\n- update(id, fields) → WorkItem\n- transition(id, new_state) → WorkItem\n- list(filters) → Vec<WorkItem>\n- search(query) → Vec<WorkItem>\n- comment(id, message)\n- next() → Option<WorkItem> (highest priority ready item)\n\nOptional methods (capability-gated):\n- add_dependency(blocker, blocked)\n- set_parent(child, parent)\n- triage() → scores/recommendations\n\nDesign constraints:\n- Trait is async\n- Methods accept/return domain model types (WorkItem), not provider types\n- Each method documents whether it's required or optional\n- Ownership annotations: which fields the adapter controls vs edict controls\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Trait compiles\n- Native bones adapter can implement it\n- No Jira/GitHub-specific types in trait signatures\n- Doc comments cover semantics and error conditions"}	blake3:1jBjeyZMOB0ccSsU-gILFnUSNQ1J9wezqICKykIWtQU
1772926293933654	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvhQE		item.update	bn-y8xf	{"field":"description","value":"Define how edict discovers what a Tasks adapter can do and handles missing capabilities.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Capability model for Tasks:\n   - Required: create, get, update, transition, list, comment\n   - Optional: dependencies, parent-child, triage/scoring, search, urgency levels, custom fields\n   - Edict queries capabilities before using optional features\n   - Graceful degradation: e.g., no dependencies → skip dependency graph, no triage → use simple FIFO\n\n2. Error semantics:\n   - Idempotency: which operations are safe to retry? Duplicate detection?\n   - Retry policy: exponential backoff, max retries, circuit breaker\n   - Rate limiting: Jira and GitHub both have rate limits — adapter reports them, edict respects them\n   - Transient vs permanent errors: adapter classifies, edict acts accordingly\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Capability enum defined for Tasks family\n- Degradation behavior documented for every optional capability\n- Error types defined with retry guidance\n- Rate limit protocol defined (covers both Jira and GitHub API limits)"}	blake3:HysG-bFRGZ3KD4UccdGgtzANDI3GMikaT5aDowJrh5c
1772926298144192	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvhgE		item.update	bn-1d8o	{"field":"description","value":"Build conformance tests and adapter implementations for Tasks.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Conformance test suite: exercises every required Tasks trait method, checks invariants, validates error handling and capability reporting\n2. Fake/in-memory adapter: implements Tasks trait with in-memory storage (no external deps)\n3. Native bones adapter: wraps bn CLI as a Tasks adapter\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Fake adapter passes full conformance suite\n- Native bones adapter passes full conformance suite\n- Tests are reusable: Jira and GitHub adapters (P5) will run the same suite\n- Tests cover: CRUD, state transitions, concurrent access, error conditions, capability queries"}	blake3:TXCVJZoiKJXSmalLgmi-37OtDgCsYjtBAlR53wG-Ggc
1772926316196613	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvhwE		item.update	bn-1m4f	{"field":"description","value":"Build the system that lets edict generate provider-specific instructions and commands from packs.\n\nScope narrowed: only task tracker is pluggable. Packs configure which Tasks adapter to use and how to render bones-related commands in AGENTS.md and templates.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Pack schema defined (which task tracker, field ownership, state mappings)\n- AGENTS.md bones sections generated from pack, not hardcoded\n- Agent loop commands (bn create, bn do, bn done, etc.) rendered per-provider\n- Native bones pack reproduces current behavior exactly"}	blake3:bSMVfxbSILY_ubMnuw9CQOgALgsVFJlNvlwLgHxUsdg
1772926316934843	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEviAE		item.update	bn-1ftr	{"field":"description","value":"Define the pack schema for task tracker configuration.\n\nA pack specifies:\n- Which Tasks adapter to use (bones, jira, github-issues)\n- Provider connection config (API URL, project key, repo, etc.)\n- State mapping: canonical states ↔ provider states\n- Field ownership: which fields edict controls vs provider controls\n- Capability overrides: disable optional features even if adapter supports them\n- Template overrides: custom AGENTS.md sections, command examples\n\nPack composition:\n- Base pack (ships with edict, one per provider)\n- Org overlay (org-specific policy: naming conventions, required labels, etc.)\n- Validation: catch conflicts (e.g., state mapping references nonexistent provider state)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Schema defined in TOML\n- Validation catches at least: missing required fields, invalid state mappings, unknown provider\n- A pack can be loaded and composed with an overlay"}	blake3:M3QH7kajTh5XgqUUKnxuoIKuVlnyDm6GglNUdvfY6bg
1772926318068412	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEviQE		item.update	bn-27tk	{"field":"description","value":"Implement a native bones pack that reproduces edict's current behavior.\n\nCritical validation: the new pack system must produce identical output to the current hardcoded templates when using the bones adapter.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Native bones pack defining: state mappings (open/doing/done), all capabilities enabled, edict owns all fields\n- AGENTS.md bones sections generated from pack templates instead of hardcoded agents-managed.md\n- Agent loop commands (bn create, bn do, bn done, bn next, bn show, bn triage) rendered from pack\n- Hook commands rendered from pack\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- edict sync with native bones pack produces functionally equivalent output to current edict sync\n- All existing evals still pass\n- No regression in agent behavior"}	blake3:whak8hEDhdX_HHE31PadPSmIk4WwhNtICla1_iMZyVI
1772926325322916	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvigE		item.update	bn-2opv	{"field":"title","value":"P4: build Jira and GitHub Issues pack skeletons"}	blake3:IPdl0Qz4ebk_LFqzw6hkTquO6KHd-mxeZQTgyepZ0Uw
1772926325334430	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEviwE		item.update	bn-2opv	{"field":"description","value":"Create pack definitions for Jira and GitHub Issues task trackers. Skeleton only — actual adapter implementation is in P5.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Jira pack: state mappings (To Do/In Progress/Done → open/doing/done), field ownership (Jira owns priority, edict owns assignee), capability declarations\n- GitHub Issues pack: state mappings (open/closed → open+doing/done), label-as-state conventions, capability declarations\n- AGENTS.md sections generated per-pack (e.g., \"create issue\" instead of \"bn create\", Jira CLI or API commands instead of bn commands)\n- Documentation of capability gaps vs bones (what degrades per provider)\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED:\n- Confirm state mappings for Jira (depends on target org's Jira workflow)\n- Confirm label conventions for GitHub Issues (e.g., \"in-progress\" label = doing state?)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Both packs load and validate without errors\n- edict sync with each pack produces coherent AGENTS.md\n- Capability gaps documented"}	blake3:Pi5ZgfMKp3tXhZlczfWjOeiqUH37ga5qsZ-2OG8xujw
1772926332073506	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvjAE		item.update	bn-1ex1	{"field":"title","value":"pluggable-tooling P5: Jira and GitHub Issues adapters"}	blake3:yNuHIKPRF316rCMTgzMkGXkxX8dykNoeMmOa3Bswozk
1772926332080638	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvjQE		item.update	bn-1ex1	{"field":"description","value":"Implement the Tasks adapter for Jira and GitHub Issues.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Jira adapter passes conformance test suite from P3\n- GitHub Issues adapter passes conformance test suite from P3\n- Both adapters handle rate limiting and error recovery\n- ExternalRef mappings created for every synced entity\n- Narrow inbound ingestion working (status changes made in Jira/GitHub reflected in edict)"}	blake3:lUdo5jWJmZixPatqN5VMyFldmU7LjZZyfp08_IyH_w4
1772926337563833	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvjgE		item.update	bn-2fgd	{"field":"title","value":"P5: set up Jira and GitHub API access"}	blake3:DlFZKwVMCq5bBMFnDqCkSnDy2BnpLNccVrN685L4rsc
1772926337575717	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvjwE		item.update	bn-2fgd	{"field":"description","value":"Set up API access for Jira and GitHub for adapter development and testing.\n\nUSER ACTION REQUIRED — this task is entirely on you:\n\nJira:\n- Create API token (or OAuth app) with project read/write access\n- Provide base URL, project key, and credentials\n- Designate test project\n\nGitHub:\n- Create PAT or GitHub App with repo, issues scopes\n- Provide token and target repo(s)\n- Designate test repository\n\nDeliverable: credentials stored securely (env vars or secrets file) and documented in a non-committed .env.example\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Each provider's API is reachable with provided credentials\n- Test resources (Jira project, GitHub repo) exist and are writable"}	blake3:KDp8TU4-WyDwsRUJkeerQVWbLFtEUZ8_fERJ1-2aI10
1772926342712195	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvkAE		item.update	bn-2ou4	{"field":"title","value":"P5: implement Jira and GitHub Issues Tasks adapters"}	blake3:qdO3tEkrginmWZ2mSOR7mpntxu2bs4Ez8m83vknk7Hg
1772926342742103	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvkQE		item.update	bn-2ou4	{"field":"description","value":"Implement the Tasks trait for Jira and GitHub Issues.\n\nJira adapter:\n- Create/update issues via Jira REST API\n- Map WorkItem states to Jira workflow statuses (per pack config)\n- Sync comments bidirectionally\n- Handle Jira's rate limits and pagination\n- Create ExternalRef mappings (internal ID ↔ PROJ-123)\n\nGitHub Issues adapter:\n- Create/update issues via GitHub API\n- Map WorkItem states to open/closed + labels\n- Sync comments\n- Handle GitHub's rate limits and pagination\n- Create ExternalRef mappings (internal ID ↔ org/repo#42)\n\nBoth adapters:\n- Implement required Tasks trait methods\n- Declare capabilities honestly (e.g., GitHub Issues: no native dependencies)\n- Idempotent operations (safe to replay)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Both adapters pass the conformance test suite from P3\n- Rate limiting works (backs off when throttled)\n- ExternalRef mappings created for every projected entity"}	blake3:l6cJbOqpayRZCNL99c1x1HsvRVR0L29XGCkzPX16umY
1772926351112930	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvkgE		item.update	bn-bh89	{"field":"title","value":"P5: implement inbound ingestion and reconciliation"}	blake3:KvN_XT5Y6aBEpVtZvtNyJOTG7XC-THeGFxoVIszcekk
1772926351130224	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvkwE		item.update	bn-bh89	{"field":"description","value":"Implement narrow inbound event handling for Jira and GitHub Issues.\n\nInbound scope (confirm in P0 ADR):\n- Jira: status changes and comment additions made by humans in Jira UI\n- GitHub: issue state changes, label changes, comment additions made in GitHub UI\n\nNOT in scope for v1:\n- Full bidirectional sync\n- Real-time webhooks (polling is acceptable for v1)\n- New issue creation flowing inward (edict creates work items, not the other way)\n\nReconciliation:\n- Periodic drift check: compare edict WorkItem state vs external issue state\n- Log discrepancies to audit trail\n- Conflict resolution per field ownership (edict-owned fields: edict wins; external-owned fields: external wins)\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED:\n- Confirm which inbound events to support in v1\n- Confirm polling interval (proposed: 60s for active work, 5min for idle)\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Inbound status changes update edict WorkItem state correctly\n- Drift detection catches: state mismatch, missing external entity, orphaned ref\n- Audit log records all reconciliation actions\n- Conflict resolution follows field ownership rules from P2"}	blake3:bmvK7iL2X_eFeU1Sg9i72jkY5kTB2C04NpLGjaXGGxI
1772926358014523	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvlAE		item.update	bn-30fe	{"field":"description","value":"Wire the reference workflow end-to-end using Jira or GitHub Issues as the task tracker.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Reference workflow (from P0) completes using an external task tracker instead of bones\n- Agent creates work item in Jira/GitHub, transitions states, adds comments throughout the cycle\n- ExternalRef mappings correct at every step\n- Degradation works: features the external tracker doesn't support are skipped gracefully\n- Integration tests and docs complete"}	blake3:fj8rPPiKr7MmbkId3H2NeRyitWwGb1GOkJ64vNp8gws
1772926363987279	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvlQE		item.update	bn-1rut	{"field":"description","value":"Run the reference workflow from start to finish using Jira and GitHub Issues adapters.\n\nSteps (assuming worker cycle reference workflow):\n1. Agent triages — queries work items from Jira/GitHub Issues via Tasks adapter\n2. Agent claims work item, creates workspace (maw — unchanged)\n3. Agent implements, commits\n4. Review created via seal (unchanged), review cycle completes\n5. Workspace merged via maw (unchanged)\n6. Work item transitioned to done in Jira/GitHub via Tasks adapter\n7. Comments posted at each step via Tasks adapter\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Full cycle completes with Jira adapter\n- Full cycle completes with GitHub Issues adapter\n- ExternalRef mappings correct at every step\n- Degradation works: disable optional capabilities, workflow still completes\n- Agent prompts/templates render correct commands for the active provider"}	blake3:DvnYax0oZTgHIJnTADnni7uaQKO0Zp7HIgUQlwsBfD8
1772926371445382	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvlgE		item.update	bn-3a8i	{"field":"description","value":"Build test and documentation infrastructure for the task tracker adapter MVP.\n\nDeliverables:\n1. Integration tests:\n   - Happy path: full reference workflow with fake Tasks adapter\n   - Adapter failure: Tasks adapter fails mid-workflow, verify degradation\n   - Rate limiting: adapter throttles, verify backoff\n   - Capability variation: run workflow with reduced capabilities (no deps, no triage)\n\n2. Failure injection:\n   - Network failure between edict and Jira/GitHub API\n   - Stale ExternalRef (external issue deleted)\n   - State conflict (human changed issue status while agent was working)\n\n3. Documentation:\n   - Runbook: troubleshooting adapter failures, reconciliation drift\n   - Onboarding guide: how to set up edict with Jira or GitHub Issues\n   - Pack authoring guide: how to create a new task tracker pack\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Integration tests run in CI with fake adapter (no real credentials needed)\n- At least 5 failure injection scenarios tested\n- Onboarding guide covers Jira and GitHub Issues setup end-to-end"}	blake3:kbLgEGWxRRPRcpBLzKiPnCRRwsiE0xxQPHvjkJQyq-w
1772926375302312	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvlwE		item.update	bn-1bny	{"field":"description","value":"Prove the Tasks adapter contract isn't overfit to Jira and GitHub Issues.\n\nImplement a third task tracker to stress-test the abstraction.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Third provider's adapter passes conformance suite without contract changes (or contracts fixed if needed)\n- Documented what was overfit and what generalized cleanly\n- All three providers work with the same pack system\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED: Choose third task tracker (e.g., Linear, Notion, Asana, Shortcut, Azure DevOps)."}	blake3:bEupEaCXNJPPNWRGUV9TvX5ucSm_HUdCWUvZHrbyxaE
1772926381324237	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvmAE		item.update	bn-1njj	{"field":"title","value":"P7: choose and implement third task tracker adapter"}	blake3:C0QegP36Fp2lgkcItzmqxwx9XBOIW2UWDlq0hUl4-VY
1772926381328287	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvmQE		item.update	bn-1njj	{"field":"description","value":"Implement a third task tracker to validate the Tasks adapter contract.\n\nUSER DECISION REQUIRED:\n- Choose third task tracker. Options:\n  a) Linear — clean API, different state model (no separate \"kind\" concept, uses labels heavily)\n  b) Notion databases — very different paradigm (schema-per-database, rich properties)\n  c) Asana — sections-as-states, custom fields, portfolio hierarchy\n  d) Azure DevOps — enterprise, complex work item types, area paths\n  e) Something else\n\nThe choice should maximize contract stress-testing. Linear is probably the easiest and still a good test. Notion would be the most rigorous.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- Third adapter passes conformance test suite from P3\n- Pack loads, validates, and produces correct AGENTS.md\n- Document which assumptions broke"}	blake3:CyT3hNGqW-CmCKqf7pH3RAe0lkHuw2zDFCUwpcs91V8
1772926385451692	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvmgE		item.update	bn-1qv0	{"field":"description","value":"After implementing the third task tracker, assess and fix any overfit in the contracts.\n\nDeliverables:\n- Audit report: which Tasks trait methods, capability flags, or WorkItem fields were overfit\n- Contract fixes: generalize overfit abstractions\n- Regression check: Jira and GitHub Issues adapters still pass after fixes\n- Final assessment: is the Tasks contract genuinely provider-agnostic?\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- All three adapters pass conformance suite after any contract changes\n- No provider-specific types or assumptions remain in core domain model\n- Documented lessons learned for future adapter authors"}	blake3:3Kk1CON6RCIAmbAJ2vLBLbe---qDdxlNRQiA9509LPA
1772927372403989	edict-dev	itc:v3:AWLkkmTOfzk5kQAAAAAAQeqtbv7rtAAAAAEvmwE		item.comment	bn-1zzt	{"body":"Discussion notes (2026-03-07):\n\nScoping conversation progressively narrowed the project:\n\n1. Started with 4 adapter families (Comms, Tasks, Review, Identity) for Slack/Jira/GitHub\n2. Realized Slack can't replace rite (no claims, hooks, coordination) — it's just I/O\n3. Realized seal stays native too — GitHub PR reviews are structurally different\n4. Narrowed to task tracker pluggability only (bones → Jira/GitHub Issues)\n5. Realized agents need bones' speed and features (triage, deps, parent-child) for operational decomposition — Jira would be a bottleneck for the dozens of operations per work cycle\n6. Natural split: Jira = external interface for humans, bones = operational layer for agents. Adapter becomes a \"bridge\" not a \"replacement\"\n7. Questioned whether even the bridge is worth building — user can manually create bones from Jira tickets\n8. Concluded Jira is too complex and configurable to adapter-ize — every org's Jira is a different product\n9. Company in question uses GitHub for code reviews only, not issues\n\nDecision: shelve entirely. Solve it when there's a real customer with a specific, bounded need. The 8-phase plan was overengineered for a problem that doesn't exist yet.\n\nSource-of-truth decisions made during discussion (preserved for future reference):\n- Split ownership (Option C) with migration path toward A\n- Non-goals: not a generic workflow engine, no full bidirectional sync, not multi-tenant, not a replacement for external tools\n- Bones stays as the operational task tracker — any future integration would bridge, not replace"}	blake3:JuSoS-hgOkA_BMWfGhkksWlubBGLcLXFk-OG36HFFVU
